    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Philada.</placeName>
                <date>July 26. 1865</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philada.</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir.</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">It may possibly be known to you<lb/> that a controversy has arisen
                in the Christian Church<lb/> regarding the use in public worship of hymns of<lb/>
                praise, which are not found in the canon of<lb/> Sacred Scripture. The example of
                the ancient Jew-<lb/>ish “church” has been claimed as a precedent a=<lb/>gainst
                their use. As this controversy has arisen in<lb/> days when Talmudic and cognate
                studies are less<lb/> zealously pursued among Christian Scholars, than<lb/> in the
                days of <persName>Lightfoot</persName> and <persName>Gill</persName>, the subject
                is<lb/> one which we must refer to those whose peculiar<lb/> studies fit them to
                solve the difficulty. Your wide<lb/> and eminent reputation as a scholar has
                led<lb/> us to trouble you with the following inquiries<lb/> your kind attention to
                which will much oblige<lb/> a large number of your fellow citizens.</p>
            <p>I—Were there any other hymns of praise than<lb/> the psalms of
                    <persName>David</persName>, sued in the ancient-<lb/>temple or synagogue service
                of the Jewish<lb/> “church” prior to the final destruction of</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the <placeName>Holy City</placeName> by <persName>Titus</persName>?</p>
            <p>II—If so, were these other hymns of praise<lb/> taken exclusively from the canonical
                scrip-<lb/>tures or not?</p>
            <p>III—Does the three-fold distinction laid down<lb/> by <persName>Paul</persName> in
                his Epistle to Colossians II. 16.<lb/> and to the Ephesians V.19. refer to any
                recog-<lb/>nized division or arrangement of the Book<lb/> of Psalms, or is it a
                general description of the<lb/> species of sacred poetry in current use at that<lb/>
                time?</p>
            <p>IV. If there were in use hymns of praise<lb/> not to be found in the canonical
                scriptures<lb/> are they still extant, and can you refer us to<lb/> any work easily
                obtained which contains<lb/> either them, or any information on the<lb/>
                subject.</p>
            <p>V. Was the entire Book of Psalms used in<lb/> the ancient temple or synagogue
                service<lb/> and if not, what part <hi rend="underline">was</hi> used?</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">We are very sorry to trouble you<lb/> with such a long list of
                queries, but<lb/> hope that you will have it in your power<lb/> to give us an answer
                at an early</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>day, without putting yourself to any in-<lb/>convenience</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">Yours very Truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">
                <persName role="author">George S. Chambers</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">
                <persName role="author">R. E. Thompson</persName>
            </p>
            <p>Address us—<placeName><hi rend="underline">Box 901</hi>—<hi rend="underline">Philada.
                        Post Office</hi></placeName></p>
        </body>
